# Deploy to: verify/edit /etc/fstab on Pi
#
# Pi OS Bookworm sets noatime on the root ext4 partition by default.
# This file is a reference snippet — verify it's present before assuming.
#
# Verify noatime is active:
#   cat /proc/mounts | grep ' / ' | grep noatime
#   -> If this returns output, noatime is active. You're done.
#
# If noatime is MISSING from /proc/mounts:
#   1. Edit /etc/fstab and add noatime to the root partition options:
#      PARTUUID=xxxxxxxx-02  /  ext4  defaults,noatime  0  1
#   2. Apply immediately without rebooting:
#      sudo mount -o remount /
#   3. Verify: cat /proc/mounts | grep ' / ' | grep noatime
#
# Why noatime matters:
#   By default, Linux updates atime (last access time) on every file read.
#   On an SD card, this means every read triggers a write — doubling the
#   write load and accelerating card wear. noatime disables atime updates
#   entirely. Since this is a read-mostly device (SSH sessions, config files),
#   the loss of atime tracking has no practical impact.
#
#   noatime vs relatime: relatime (Linux default since 2009) still writes
#   atime when mtime is newer than atime. noatime never writes atime.
#   For SD card longevity, noatime is strictly better.

# Example /etc/fstab root partition line with noatime:
# (Replace PARTUUID with the actual value from your system)
PARTUUID=xxxxxxxx-02  /  ext4  defaults,noatime  0  1
